## 5. Function 1 — Provide Structure and Governance

### Key idea

A PMO establishes the **rules, frameworks, and reference points** that make project execution more consistent and more manageable. 

### What it includes

| Element                   | Meaning                                             |
| ------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------- |
| Standardized processes    | Teams follow a common approach                      |
| Common methodologies      | Projects are run in a coherent way                  |
| Governance framework      | Roles, expectations, and controls are clear         |
| Centralized documentation | Teams can access shared information                 |
| Performance metrics       | Progress and outcomes can be monitored consistently |

### Why it matters

Without structure, teams use different methods, make inconsistent decisions, and create confusion, delays, and budget overruns. With structure, communication becomes easier, expectations become clearer, and outcomes become more predictable. 

### Memory sentence

**Structure reduces chaos and increases predictability.**

### Interview phrasing

> “One of the PMO’s core functions is to provide structure and governance by standardizing ways of working, centralizing project information, and creating the control mechanisms needed for predictable delivery.”

---

## 6. Function 2 — Ensure Alignment with Organizational Strategy

### Key idea

A PMO helps the organization invest its time, people, and budget in the projects that matter most. 

### What it includes

| Element                              | Meaning                                                |
| ------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------ |
| Collaboration with senior management | Strategic priorities are understood                    |
| Project prioritization               | High-value initiatives are favored                     |
| Portfolio visibility                 | The organization can see what supports long-term goals |
| Resource focus                       | Effort is directed where it creates most value         |

### Why it matters

Projects can be well run and still be the wrong projects. Strategic alignment ensures that the organization does not waste effort on initiatives that do not contribute meaningfully to broader objectives. 

### Memory sentence

**Alignment ensures the organization is doing the right work, not just doing work well.**

### Interview phrasing

> “A strong PMO acts as a bridge between execution and strategy, helping leadership prioritize initiatives that contribute most directly to organizational goals and long-term value.”

---

## 7. Function 3 — Enhance Efficiency and Effectiveness in Delivery

### Key idea

A PMO improves project outcomes by strengthening the capability of teams and supporting them throughout execution. 

### What it includes

| Element                | Meaning                                 |
| ---------------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| Resource support       | Teams have access to what they need     |
| Skills and training    | Capability is developed intentionally   |
| Continuous monitoring  | Problems are identified early           |
| Ongoing support        | Teams receive guidance to stay on track |
| Continuous improvement | Delivery practices get better over time |

### Why it matters

Projects succeed more consistently when teams are supported, obstacles are addressed proactively, and learning is built into the delivery model. This improves both speed and quality. 

### Memory sentence

**Support improves execution quality and delivery confidence.**

### Interview phrasing

> “The PMO enhances delivery effectiveness by equipping teams with resources, visibility, and support mechanisms that improve quality, reduce delays, and enable proactive problem solving.”

